{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531173"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14582"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14582"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.02,0.04,0.41,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7275"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"2338"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43541"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe pain, swelling, and redness in his left hand. He has a medical history of psoriasis, gout, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and osteoarthritis. His regular medications include secukinumab, allopurinol, colchicine, metformin, gliclazide, perindopril, and paracetamol. He has recently had reduced oral intake following a gastrointestinal illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but not distressed. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His left hand shows diffuse erythema and swelling, with marked tenderness over the distal and proximal interphalangeal joints of the second finger. Multiple chalky white nodules are visible around these joints. He has plaque psoriasis present on his bilateral upper limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 13.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 55 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 136 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EX-ray of the left hand shows erosive changes with overhanging edges in the second finger interphalangeal joints, and soft tissue swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to diagnose his condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biopsy of plaque psoriasis","Dual energy CT of left hand","MRI of left hand","Joint aspirate of left DIP/PIP joint","No further investigation required"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute gout flare with visible tophi (chalky white nodules), which are pathognomonic for gout. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigation\u003C/strong\u003E is required to make the diagnosis in this case, as the presence of tophi is highly suggestive for the diagnosis of gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual energy CT\u003C/strong\u003E of the hand, while being able to detect and quantify urate crystal deposits, is unnecessary when tophi are already visible. It may be useful in cases where the diagnosis is unclear or to monitor disease progression, but is not indicated here. It may be particularly useful if the clinical and radiological features suggested a possibility of psoriatic arthritis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint aspirate\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing acute gout in cases where the diagnosis is uncertain, as it can demonstrate negatively birefringent urate crystals under polarized light microscopy. However, it is invasive and unnecessary when tophi are already visible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E of the hand would show soft tissue inflammation and bone erosions but cannot specifically diagnose gout. It would be more useful in evaluating for osteomyelitis or other soft tissue pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy of plaque psoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E would not help diagnose gout. While this patient does have psoriasis, the presentation is classic for gout with visible tophi, and a skin biopsy would only confirm the already known psoriasis diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key learning point is that visible tophi are pathognomonic for gout and no further diagnostic testing is required. The presence of tophi indicates chronic gout with prolonged hyperuricaemia, and management should focus on treating the acute flare while ensuring appropriate long-term urate-lowering therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tophi are pathognomonic for gout and establish the diagnosis without need for further investigation.","Joint aspiration remains the gold standard for diagnosing acute gout when the diagnosis is uncertain.","Dual energy CT can detect and quantify urate deposits but is not necessary when tophi are visible."],"references":["Stauder SK, Peloso PM. Dual-Energy computed tomography has additional prognostic value over clinical measures in gout including tophi: A systematic literature review. The Journal of Rheumatology. 2022 Nov 1;49(11):1256-68. Available online at ; https://www.jrheum.org/content/49/11/1256?utm_source=TrendMD\u0026utm_medium=cpc\u0026utm_campaign=J_Rheumatol_TrendMD_0","Clebak KT, Morrison A, Croad JR. Gout: Rapid evidence review. American family physician. 2020 Nov 1;102(9):533-8. Available online at ; https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2020/1101/p533.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42587"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42587"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T18:01:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T18:03:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7275"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57128"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n